<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900501-0060</DOCNO><DOCID>900501-0060.</DOCID><HL>   Aetna Files Lawsuit   Against Massachusetts   Over Car Insurance</HL><DATE>05/01/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AET</CO><IN>INSURANCE (INS)</IN><LP>   BOSTON (AP) -- Aetna Casualty andamp; Surety Co., a unit ofAetna Life andamp; Casualty Co. of Hartford, Conn., filed suitagainst the state, claiming that Massachusetts lawscontrolling withdrawal from the state's car insurance marketare unconstitutional.   &quot;The insurance commissioner sets the prices so pricecompetition is nonexistent,&quot; said John J. Martin, presidentof Aetna's personal financing security division.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;Worse still, an insurer that decides to leave the privatepassenger auto insurance market in light of such conditionsconfronts a massive hurdle to any orderly exit from thatmarket because it must pay what amounts to extortion or loseall its licenses to any other insurance business,&quot; Mr. Martinsaid in a statement.   Dorothy Krenzer, a spokeswoman for the state InsuranceDivision, said the agency wouldn't have any comment untilCommissioner Timothy Gailey has reviewed documents on thesuit.   John Hawkins, an Aetna spokesman, said the firm seeks toexit from the Massachusetts car insurance market.   Mr. Hawkins said: &quot;Over a period of years, we have eitherlost money or made so little that it's not an acceptablebusiness environment for us.&quot;   Under state law, insurers must pay an assessment for eightyears in order to withdraw from the Massachusetts carinsurance market without losing their license to sell otherkinds of insurance.   The insurance commissioner also can revoke all licensesgranted an insurer if it pulls out of the car insurancemarket because of the state's insurance laws.</TEXT></DOC>